### Footnotes

<span id="fn_475"></span>[43:476](0010119.htm#fr_475.md) <span
id="iv.iv.xxi-p1.1"></span>

<span id="iv.iv.xxi-p2"></span> The translation is here very doubtful.
Wake renders the words <span class="Greek"><span
id="iv.iv.xxi-p2.1"></span>μηνὸς ἱσταμένου</span>, “of the *present*
month.”

<span id="fn_476"></span>[43:477](0010119.htm#fr_476.md) <span
id="iv.iv.xxi-p2.2"></span>

<span id="iv.iv.xxi-p3"></span> Great obscurity hangs over the
chronology here indicated. According to Usher, the Smyrnæans began the
month Xanthicus on the 25th of March. But the seventh day before the
Kalends of May is the 25th of April. Some, therefore, read <span
class="Greek"><span id="iv.iv.xxi-p3.1"></span>᾽Απριλλίων</span> instead
of <span class="Greek"><span id="iv.iv.xxi-p3.2"></span>Μαίων</span>.
The great Sabbath is that before the passover. The “eighth hour” may
correspond either to our 8 <span class="upper"><span
id="iv.iv.xxi-p3.3"></span>a.m. </span>or 2 <span class="upper"><span
id="iv.iv.xxi-p3.4"></span>p.m.</span>

<span id="fn_477"></span>[43:478](0010119.htm#fr_477.md) <span
id="iv.iv.xxi-p3.6"></span>

<span id="iv.iv.xxi-p4"></span> Called before (chap. xii.) *Asiarch*.

